Here's the LaTeX code to recreate the image showing external economies of agglomeration through a shift in the production function:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
    % Axes
    \draw[->] (0,0) -- (6,0) node[below] {$k$};
    \draw[->] (0,0) -- (0,4) node[left] {$y$};

    % Axes labels
    \node[below] at (3,-0.5) {Input (capital per worker)};
    \node[rotate=90, left] at (-0.5,2) {Output per worker};

    % Production functions
    \draw[thick] (0,0) .. controls (1.5,1.5) and (3,2.3) .. (5,2.8) node[right] {$y = G(N)f(k)$};
    \draw[thick] (0,0) .. controls (1.5,1.8) and (3,2.8) .. (5,3.5) node[right] {$y = G(N')f(k)$};

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

This code creates:
1. A coordinate system with labeled axes for capital per worker (k) and output per worker (y)
2. Two production function curves showing the shift from G(N)f(k) to G(N')f(k)
3. The curves are drawn to match the concave shape in the original image
4. Proper labeling of both axes and curves

The visual demonstrates how external economies of agglomeration cause a firm's production function to shift upward when city size increases from N to N', indicating higher productivity at all levels of capital input.

